<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 10<br /><b>Date:</b> 2020-04-19<br /><b>Votes:</b> 18<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
Got to love an original rolling release! <br />Install once and someday your grand grand kids would inherit the same installation. (no fake hype every six month or so about a new version coming up, you are always running the latest release).<br /><br />Its lightweight cause you choose what to install on your PC from ground up! , and I feel I experienced no(?!!) dependency nightmare since I moved to Arch!<br /><br />AUR (Arch User Repository) is a good addition. Although I just use a couple of packages from AUR,  it is good to know that when I need a new package that is not available in the main repository (e.g. Brave browser) I most probably can find it on AUR.<br /><br />For me the best selling point was the rolling release and the customization that being able and free to choose what packages build up my OS brings to the table , Other than that all Linux distros are awesome and will make some people with different tastes and needs happy.<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
