<tr style="outline: thin solid black">
<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 9<br /><b>Date:</b> 2020-03-23<br /><b>Votes:</b> 8<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
Excellent distro for people who don't mind putting in a little work to make it run the way they want to. It's not for absolute beginners, but I think it's a good "final exam" distro for experienced beginners who want to expand their knowledge. Arch is harder to set up than something like Ubuntu, but it's not that bad, and its KISS design makes it easier to get under the hood and learn from it without all of the bespoke tools that other distros carry. Not to mention the amazing Arch Wiki, which honestly I think is a more valuable resource to the Linux community than the distro itself.<br /><br />Great selection of programs in the repos. Even more in the AUR, as long as you're careful whose scripts you trust. The only reason I dock a point is because pacman could stand to be more fault-tolerant. Users are expected to check the official announcements before installing updates in case manual intervention is needed, which feels like an unrealistic expectation, particularly for a rolling release distro. But hey, at least pacman is fast.<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
