<tr style="outline: thin solid black">
<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 10<br /><b>Date:</b> 2019-11-24<br /><b>Votes:</b> 1<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
I've been using Linux distros of all kinds, maybe 7 or 8 years, and I've always had Arch in the back of my mind.  I recently installed it on a laptop a couple of months ago.. an ultrabook-type laptop with no ethernet.  I decided to use UEFI and encryption.. so I was jumping in the deep end.  I admit, it took a few tries since recently there has been a change, and you should be sure to add linux (and others) to pacstrap when installing.. since the kernel and user utilities are no longer included in base.  Your pacstrap will need to have everything for your setup if you're going for encryption, as it saves a LOT of hassle.  <br /><br />It's now my new favorite. Runs like a champ, most responsive and so far stable distro I ever used.  I gave it a 10 because it does what it is intended perfectly.  This is THE way to build your OS around a well maintained rolling distro, with a great community and mountains of online help.  I think if it came with a DE or anything else, it would certainly be a lower score, no matter what, since you will be centering on something many are guaranteed not to like.  It's a core, and a damn good one.  I'm installing it on my daily driver later today, as I've been using the Arch laptop for a while now and it looks, feels and responds far, far better than Windows 10.  Going back to Win10 even for short visits is kind of depressing now, since I've experienced the best.  <br /><br />Most will say "not for beginners.."  And this may be true for most, but if you're the type that doesn't just want to try a new OS, but to learn about Linux, Arch is by far the best damn teacher you'll ever get.  The experience will give you the best understanding in the shortest time, out of any and all other "pre-built" distros.  You only need to watch some Youtube vids, read some of the manuals, install it on a VM a few times, and when you're ready, put it on metal.  Once you do, you'll never go back.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
