<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 2<br /><b>Date:</b> 2019-10-07<br /><b>Votes:</b> 2<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
I used to think - and freely shared with people - that Windows was the worst OS ever conceived, let alone implemented. Having spent considerable time (which is precious because I can't get more of it) reading the Arch wiki for instructions on installation I have formed an opinion.<br /><br />I'm sure that Arch Linux quite good (based on the GNU/Linux kernel, etc), but the creators seem to have gone out of their way to make its installation an unprofitable pain in the ass so that nerds (and would-be nerds) can congratulation each other in their mutual masturbation sessions on the wiki. <br /><br />Arch Linux installation is awful. The entire point of switching to Linux is to have a better, safer, and more intuitive way accomplish end-user computing without your OS becoming a profession or a hobby. Canonical figured that out. So did Redhat and of course, there is abundant fault to be found in both, but they got the basics of how humans can use a computer to help them do their work, without becoming their work. A fluid will always seek the course of least resistance. How else can one explain the global popularity of the the two crappiest operating systems ever implemented (Windows and OS X)?<br /><br />I am certain that Arch Linux has, and will keep a base of enthusiastic users, but it will never compete with vastly better options that focus on making a better OS, and not on changing human nature.<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
