<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 9<br /><b>Date:</b> 2019-09-24<br /><b>Votes:</b> 5<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
Arch... Once you know what you're doing, it's a "setup and go" OS that gives you exactly what you want... and nothing more.<br /><br />You can get the packages you want from the repos, so you never have to go compile source (And if it's not in the repos, it's in the AUR). I have Xfce4, Jack2, Steam, LiteIDE, Hugo, and Go all packaged on here. Simple, straightforward, easy, no bloat, and a huge, huge stack of packages available with a simple 'Pacman -S' in the terminal.<br /><br />That said, this OS is not for the beginner; At least, not one without an experienced guide walking them through the steps. I knock a point off of this simply because of the documentation for installing Arch on their site. In the end of that 'guide', you have no user, no password on Root, not even a bootloader. It's a void that things like Architect corrects (Another method of installing Arch), but nothing's clear without digging deep into other sites, which could turn a lot of people away.<br /><br />All in all, it's a lovely OS, I've helped multiple people install it on their systems, with it being my go-to OS for such a purpose. But if someone were to try on their own, the guide on the Arch site would easily scare them away.<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
