<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
I've been using Linux since the 90's. I also used *BSD. I've used Red Hat Linux, Mandrake, Mandriva, Fedora Core, RHEL, CentOS, Debian, Ubuntu... until a co-working introduced me to Arch Linux. All my complaints about any particular Linux Distro are now gone. You have the flexibility to make Arch Linux exactly what you want Linux to be. You're not cornered into tools that don't quite do what you want, and you are able to keep up with the current versions of most of the major software components.<br /><br />Not recommended for the new Linux User, but Linux Veterans will find that this is the final upgrade and ultimate Linux environment where you are free to run any Desktop Environment and any software you choose.<br /><br />This project isn't run by a corporation looking to gather your data. It isn't exclusive of software that may not be completely in the Freedom dimension, and doesn't depend on your monetary support. It is run by a group of highly-skilled volunteers with plenty of room for contributions from Linux Users of every level and profession.<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
