<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 10<br /><b>Date:</b> 2019-09-01<br /><b>Votes:</b> 33<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
I run Arch with a KDE Plasma desktop on a Core i5 box with 16GB ram and hardwired internet. I use it for day-to-day stuff, development, and photo processing.<br />I‚Äôve installed and used many systems over many years. My main system runs Arch.<br />The system is; stable, fast, and economical in the use of system resources.<br />Arch gives fine control over; what is installed, system configuration, and which services run. OK the initial CLI install is slower and more involved than a graphical install. But you do know about how how the system is configured. And subsequent configuration and maintenance is straightforward.<br />There are a wide range of up to date applications. I just have what I use installed on top of the base/utilities stuff. Not much point in having a load of unused stuff.<br />Package management is simple and works. Dependency handling is really good. Just remember never to type 'sudo pacman -Rcs base-devel' or you  will end up with the dark screen of death, and have to reach for the install media. That was a sad day.<br />Documentation is very comprehensive. Although you do have to get your head around the massive kit of parts at your disposal to pick out the optimum way to get what you want. And despite the wiki scrutiny people trying to keep the wiki to facts, it is very educational.<br />You get a high performance customized Linux system. I'm really glad Arch Linux exists.<br /><br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
