<tr style="outline: thin solid black">
<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 10<br /><b>Date:</b> 2019-08-10<br /><b>Votes:</b> 32<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
After using Fedora, Debian, Ubuntu for years, i am using now Arch for quite a long time, and am happy with it. The documentation on wiki is excellent, can be edited, there is a mailing list, a facebook group, and the motto is "be nice especially to beginners". The Arch people often know and use other distributions as well and focus on technical help.<br /><br />The release cycle is rolling, and in rare cases something breaks. I made the best experience by installing two kernels, "linux" and "linux-lts", the long term support version. in case one breaks just boot the other. Also installing a package like "yay" to benefit from the Arch user repository helped. <br /><br />Arch has nearly as much sofware packaged as Debian, and far more than all other distributions. The GUI can be chosen. if you like KDE put it. or Gnome, or Solus, Elementary, Xfce, Sway. If software does not work than there is usually a git package from source, so one is not bound to one version.<br /><br />While i never arrived to package software for Debian based distros like Debian or Ubuntu, or one of the RedHat distros, i found it easy to do for Arch.<br /><br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
