<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
That's a distro that you actually know what you're doing with your system and if something goes wrong you are able to fix. Absolutely no long hardness. Different than you might think, everything do not break spontaneously. If you just updated a package and that one needs to update a configuration file, update it (this potentially can avoid lots of issues) and customize something if it's necessary.<br />Everything you need to know is already on the Arch Wiki. Almost every single thing has multiple ways to get done, from de easiest to the hardest. <br />All the hardness you can have is on installation and initial configuration of everything. Then, literally everything is so easy to get done and you don't need to depend to flatpak's, snap's and anything, because almost all the applications found on the arch repository is updated and not customized by default (there are exceptions because of compability/security reasons). <br />So... With this distro you avoid lots of problems, have everything updated, pretty stable and fast (if you configure correctly) and, in lots of cases, make the actual user like me just stop hopping to another distro for better features.<br />Long live, Arch Linux!<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
