<tr style="outline: thin solid black">
<td width=30% style="border:0" valign=top>
<b>Version:</b> current<br /><b>Rating:</b> 10<br /><b>Date:</b> 2019-06-04<br /><b>Votes:</b> 8<br /><br /><br /></td>
<td width="70%" style="border:0" valign="top">
I've been learning how to use and customize the xfce4 desktop from Debian and then were using so much slower Flatpak applications because of the very old ones from the repositories. Since i've learned a lot about Linux, I figured out it's time to learn and install Arch Linux. After some days of testing and learning, now I'm running it with xfce4 with exactly the same appearance I had on Debian and ALL the applications is from Arch Official Repositories and Arch User Repositories, with a way faster, compatible and easy operational system to use, no longer hardness.<br />Here's some tips:<br />-Uninstall applications using pacman -Rs instead of -R, in order for removing the dependencies that will not be userful from another applications;<br />-Create a line on /etc/fstab of every partition you have on your internal storange like it's recommended on Arch Wiki. If you need to use the HDD/SSD with this o.s. installed on another machine, maybe the fstab will be userful for booting properly. For example my ssd that have a single partition: /dev/sda1 / ext4 discard 0 1 ;<br />-Add your user to the group wheel and sudo (if sudo doesn't exists and you want to use sudo, create it);<br />-Enable the Multilib repository if you want 32 bit applications like steam;<br />-Compile and install an AUR package manager like yaourt if you want an application that isn't on official repository;<br />-Install the xorg (metapackage) and xterm in order to run some applications (even some games on steam require that).<br />Long live, Arch Linux. Because of you, I guess I'll never hop to another distro again.<br /><br /><br /><form name=like method=get>
